🔷 Console Methods (Very Important ⭐)

Node.js provides powerful console tools.

---

1️⃣ console.log()

```javascript
console.log("Hello World");
```

✔ General output
✔ Most commonly used

---

2️⃣ console.error()

```javascript
console.error("Error occurred!");
```

✔ Shows errors clearly

---

3️⃣ console.warn()

```javascript
console.warn("Warning!");
```

✔ Displays warning messages

---

4️⃣ console.table()

```javascript
const users = [
  { name: "John", age: 25 },
  { name: "Sara", age: 22 }
];

console.table(users);
```

✔ Displays structured data

---

5️⃣ console.time() & console.timeEnd()

```javascript
console.time("Loop");

for (let i = 0; i < 1000000; i++) {}

console.timeEnd("Loop");
```

✔ Measure performance

---

6️⃣ console.dir()

```javascript
console.dir({ name: "Saakshi", skills: ["JS", "React"] });
```

✔ Displays object properties

---

7️⃣ console.clear()

```javascript
console.clear();
```

✔ Clears terminal

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Debugging with debugger Keyword

```javascript
function sum(a, b) {
  debugger;
  return a + b;
}

sum(5, 3);
```

📌 Execution pauses at `debugger`

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Run Debug Mode in Node.js

```bash
node inspect app.js
```

OR modern way:

```bash
node --inspect app.js
```

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Debugging with Chrome DevTools

Steps:

1️⃣ Run:

```bash
node --inspect app.js
```

2️⃣ Open Chrome → `chrome://inspect`
3️⃣ Click **Inspect**

✔ Add breakpoints
✔ Step through code
✔ Inspect variables

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Breakpoints

A breakpoint stops execution at a specific line.

```javascript
let a = 10;
let b = 20; // breakpoint here
let sum = a + b;
```

✔ Check variable values
✔ Analyze flow

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔷 Debugging Workflow

```text
Write Code
   ↓
Run Program
   ↓
Error Found
   ↓
Debug (console / debugger)
   ↓
Fix Issue
   ↓
Test Again
```

